description.value: Limestone figure of a seated cat or bird (sphinx?). The figure is shown in a highly schematic way, the head is broken off, a small area of the back is chipped. The front legs are the only body parts actually indicated; they are stricly parallel, straight and in a closed position. There is no indication of a tail and the hind legs are not rendered either, though it appears as though the front legs are resting on the hind paws. It is also possible that some form of a plinth was intended on which the animal was seated.  The surface is very smooth apart from the rough base.

description.value: Wooden female figure: dressed in the high style of the late Eighteenth and early Nineteenth Dynasties, this woman wears a long gala-wig that envelops her shoulders. Each thick tress is individually curled, plaited, and bound at the tip. Two shorter strands frame her face. Her broad diadem is of gold, simulated here by yellow paint. A lotus blossom at the front, its stems crossing over her head to the back of the band, was probably artificial and may well have been part of the diadem. Her dress was a large rectangular piece of sheer pleated linen, which was wrapped around the body with one fringed edge running down the front. Another section was pulled over the left shoulder and arm, and the whole was held together by a knot beneath the right breast. The woman's left foot is lost, but - unusually - both her accessories have been preserved. She holds a lotus blossom in her hanging proper right hand and a formal bouquet of stacked flowers in her left.

description.value: Terracotta squatting ithyphallic figure with jar.  A youth seated on a plain rectangular, but damaged, plinth. He is modelled in the round and naked, with a long side-lock on the left side of his shaved head, curving behind to hang down his back. A large phallus rises to wind round his waist, the glans resting against his left side. Resting on his right thigh, and held against his right side by both hands, is an amphora with handles placed midway on its body; its top, which may have had an upright rim, is damaged.  Solid; two-piece mould. Micaceous brown Nile silt with a red-brown surface, probably a slip; light-grey core. There are remains of a white dressing above the plinth, painted pink.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of naked woman. A thick plaque with a rounded top, the front showing the naked figure of a woman in high relief. Her arms are by her sides and her breasts are prominent. She has a short but full hairstyle or wig, brushed back all round, with a narrow fillet above the forehead. She probably stood on a projection from the lowest part of the plaque, now lost. The edges and the back of the plaque are square and smooth. Pressed into a one-piece mould, the edges were cut to shape. Traces of white coating in naval and red paint on the pubic area. Brown Nile silt with a thick grey-brown core, abundant fine mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of satyr. The upper part of an elderly satyr, broken from a figure, probably reclining. He is balding, with a generous beard, and his right arm is extended downwards: it is lost below the elbow. He probably leans on his left elbow, but the arm is broken away above it; a himation falls off his left shoulder, covering his arm, and part of it can be seen close to his body, under his right arm. The rear of the figure has come away at the join. Hollow, from two-piece mould, with traces of a white dressing survive; there may be red paint on his beard, but it may just be the surface of the fabric. Red-brown Nile silt with abundant mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Lower part of a wooden seated figure: the figure was seated with his hands on his thighs, but everything above the waist has been lost. The execution of the work is rather rough; the thumb of the left hand  is indicated, but the fingers are not; the right hand has been damaged. The feet end bluntly. At the level of the knees a hole has been bored through the figure from front to back, presumably to take a peg to secure the seated figure on a 'block' throne. The legs, feet, painted white to indicate a kilt.
